23/02/23, 10:25 am - Sanskar Mohan: #include <GL/glut.h>
#include <math.h>

#define PI 3.14159265

void drawCylinder(float radius, float height, int slices) {
    float angle;
    float x, y;
    float step = 2 * PI / slices;

    glBegin(GL_TRIANGLE_STRIP);
    for (int i = 0; i <= slices; i++) {
        angle = i * step;
        x = radius * cos(angle);
        y = radius * sin(angle);
        glVertex3f(x, y, 0.0);
        glVertex3f(x, y, height);
    }
    glEnd();

    glBegin(GL_POLYGON);
    for (int i = 0; i <= slices; i++) {
        angle = i * step;
        x = radius * cos(angle);
        y = radius * sin(angle);
        glVertex3f(x, y, height);
    }
    glEnd();

    glBegin(GL_POLYGON);
    for (int i = 0; i <= slices; i++) {
        angle = i * step;
        x = radius * cos(angle);
        y = radius * sin(angle);
        glVertex3f(x, y, 0.0);
    }
    glEnd();
}

void display() {
    glClear(GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT | GL_DEPTH_BUFFER_BIT);
    glMatrixMode(GL_MODELVIEW);
    glLoadIdentity();
    gluLookAt(0, 0, 5, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0);
    glColor3f(1.0, 1.0, 1.0);
    drawCylinder(1.0, 2.0, 20);
    glutSwapBuffers();
}

void reshape(int w, int h) {
    glViewport(0, 0, w, h);
    glMatrixMode(GL_PROJECTION);
    glLoadIdentity();
    gluPerspective(60, (float)w/h, 0.1, 100);
}

int main(int argc, char** argv) {
    glutInit(&argc, argv);
    glutInitDisplayMode(GLUT_DOUBLE | GLUT_RGB | GLUT_DEPTH);
    glutInitWindowSize(500, 500);
    glutCreateWindow("2D Cylinder");
    glutDisplayFunc(display);
    glutReshapeFunc(reshape);
    glutMainLoop();
    return 0;
}

#include <math.h>
#include <GL/glut.h>


void init(){
    glClearColor(1.0,1.0,1.0,0.0);
    glMatrixMode(GL_PROJECTION);
    gluOrtho2D(0,640,0,480);
}
void drawDot (GLint x, GLint y, GLfloat r, GLfloat g, GLfloat b)
{ glColor3f(r,g,b);
glPointSize(3.0);
  glBegin (GL_POINTS);
	  glVertex2i (x,y);
  glEnd();
}
void symmetricPixels (int x, int y, int xc, int yc, float r, float g, float b)
{ drawDot (xc + x, yc + y, r,g,b);
  drawDot (xc - x, yc + y,r,g,b);
  drawDot (xc + x, yc - y,r,g,b);
  drawDot (xc - x, yc - y,r,g,b);
}
void Ellipse (int a, int b, int xc, int yc, float r, float g, float bl)
{ int aSq,bSq,twoASq,twoBSq,d,dx,dy,x,y;
  aSq = a*a;
  bSq = b*b;
  twoASq = 2*aSq;
  twoBSq = 2*bSq;
  d = bSq - b*aSq + aSq/4;
  dx = 0;
  dy = twoASq*b;
  x = 0;
  y = b;
  symmetricPixels(x,y,xc,yc,r,g,bl);
  while (dx < dy)
  { x++;
    dx += twoBSq;
    if (d >= 0)
    { y--;
      dy -= twoASq;
    }
    if (d < 0)
     d += bSq + dx;
    else
     d += bSq + dx - dy;
    symmetricPixels (x,y,xc,yc,r,g,bl);
  }
  d = (int)(bSq*(x+0.5)*(x+0.5) + aSq*(y-1)*(y-1) -
                 aSq*bSq);
  while (y > 0)
  { y--;
    dy -= twoASq;
    if (d <= 0)
    { x++;
      dx += twoBSq;
    }
    if (d > 0)
         d += aSq - dy;
    else
         d += aSq -dy +dx;
    symmetricPixels(x,y,xc,yc,r,g,bl);
  }
  glFlush();
}
void display1()
{
Ellipse(100,25,320,240,1.0,1.0,0.0);
Ellipse(100,25,320,140,1.0,1.0,0.0);
glBegin(GL_LINES);
    glVertex2f(270,240);
    glVertex2f(270,140);

    
    glVertex2f(290,240);
    glVertex2f(290,140);
glEnd();

}
int main(int argc, char** argv){
glutInit(&argc, argv);
glutInitDisplayMode(GLUT_SINGLE|GLUT_RGB);
glutInitWindowSize(600, 600);
glutInitWindowPosition(100, 100);
glutCreateWindow(" Ellipse Drawing ");
    init();
    glutDisplayFunc(display1);
    glutMainLoop();
    return 0;
}

void drawDot (GLint x, GLint y, GLfloat r, GLfloat g, GLfloat b)
{ glColor3f(r,g,b);
glPointSize(3.0);
  glBegin (GL_POINTS);
	  glVertex2i (x,y);
  glEnd();
}
void symmetricPixels (int x, int y, int xc, int yc, float r, float g, float b)
{ drawDot (xc + x, yc + y, r,g,b);
  drawDot (xc - x, yc + y,r,g,b);
  drawDot (xc + x, yc - y,r,g,b);
  drawDot (xc - x, yc - y,r,g,b);
}
void Ellipse (int a, int b, int xc, int yc, float r, float g, float bl)
{ int aSq,bSq,twoASq,twoBSq,d,dx,dy,x,y;
  aSq = a*a;
  bSq = b*b;
  twoASq = 2*aSq;
  twoBSq = 2*bSq;
  d = bSq - b*aSq + aSq/4;
  dx = 0;
  dy = twoASq*b;
  x = 0;
  y = b;
  symmetricPixels(x,y,xc,yc,r,g,bl);
  while (dx < dy)
  { x++;
    dx += twoBSq;
    if (d >= 0)
    { y--;
      dy -= twoASq;
    }
    if (d < 0)
     d += bSq + dx;
    else
     d += bSq + dx - dy;
    symmetricPixels (x,y,xc,yc,r,g,bl);
  }
  d = (int)(bSq*(x+0.5)*(x+0.5) + aSq*(y-1)*(y-1) -
                 aSq*bSq);
  while (y > 0)
  { y--;
    dy -= twoASq;
    if (d <= 0)
    { x++;
      dx += twoBSq;
    }
    if (d > 0)
         d += aSq - dy;
    else
         d += aSq -dy +dx;
    symmetricPixels(x,y,xc,yc,r,g,bl);
  }
  glFlush();
}

23/02/23, 11:33 am - Anmol: #include <GL/glut.h>
#include <cmath>

const int width = 600;
const int height = 600;
const float PI = 3.14159265f;

void drawEllipse1(int a, int b) {
    glBegin(GL_POINTS);
    for (float theta = 0; theta < PI; theta += 0.035) {
        float x = a * cos(theta);
        float y = b * sin(theta);
        glVertex2f(x, y - 50);
    }

    for (float theta = PI; theta < 2 * PI; theta += 0.001) {
        float x = a * cos(theta);
        float y = b * sin(theta);
        glVertex2f(x, y - 50);
    }
    glEnd();
}

void drawEllipse2(int a, int b) {
    glBegin(GL_POINTS);
    for (float theta = 0; theta < 2 * PI; theta += 0.001) {
        float x = a * cos(theta);
        float y = b * sin(theta);
        glVertex2f(x, y + 50);
    }
    glEnd();
}

void drawlines()
{
    glBegin(GL_LINES);
    glVertex2i(-100, -50);
    glVertex2i(-100, 50);
    glEnd();

    glBegin(GL_LINES);
    glVertex2i(100, -50);
    glVertex2i(100, 50);
    glEnd();
}

void display() {
    int a = 100, b = 20;
    glMatrixMode(GL_PROJECTION);
    glLoadIdentity();
    gluOrtho2D(-320, 320, -240, 240);
    glMatrixMode(GL_MODELVIEW);
    glLoadIdentity();
    glColor3f(0.0, 0.0, 0.0);
    glPointSize(2.0);
    glTranslatef(0.0, 0.0, 0.0);

    drawEllipse1(a, b);
    drawEllipse2(a, b);
    drawlines();
    glFlush();
}

int main(int argc, char** argv) {
    glutInit(&argc, argv);
    glutInitDisplayMode(GLUT_SINGLE);
    glutInitWindowSize(width, height);
    glutInitWindowPosition(100, 100);
    glutCreateWindow("Ellipse");
    glClearColor(1.0, 1.0, 1.0, 1.0);
    glClear(GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
    glutDisplayFunc(display);
    glutMainLoop();
    return 0;
}

22/03/23, 1:32 pm - Anmol: ironment: Identify the crops that are susceptible to heat stress and the environmental conditions that may cause it.

Monitor temperature and humidity: Use sensors or weather stations to continuously measure the air temperature and relative humidity in the field.

Record plant physiological parameters: Measure plant physiological parameters such as leaf temperature, stomatal conductance, and photosynthesis rate using non-destructive techniques.

Analyze data: Analyze the collected data using statistical methods to identify trends and patterns that may indicate heat stress.

Establish thresholds: Set threshold values for the monitored parameters beyond which the crops are considered to be under heat stress.

Alert system: Develop an alert system that can notify the farmer or grower when the monitored parameters exceed the threshold values.

Implement management strategies: Based on the severity of the heat stress, implement management strategies such as irrigation, shading, or other techniques to reduce the stress on the crops.

Continuously monitor and adjust: Continuously monitor the crops and the environment and adjust management strategies as necessary to minimize the impact of heat stress.

24/03/23, 12:45 am - Anmol: To create a dataset for detection of crops under temperature stress, you would need to consider the following input parameters:

Crop species: The dataset should include information on different crops that are commonly grown under temperature stress conditions. This would typically include crops such as wheat, maize, soybean, and rice.

Temperature range: The dataset should cover a range of temperatures that are considered to be stressful for crop growth. This may vary depending on the specific crop species, but could range from 25-35°C for many crops.

Soil type: The type of soil can have a significant impact on how crops respond to temperature stress, so it is important to include information on soil type in the dataset.

Irrigation regime: The amount and frequency of irrigation can also influence how crops respond to temperature stress, so this should be taken into account when creating the dataset.

Growth stage: The dataset should include information on the growth stage of the crop when it is exposed to temperature stress. This can have a significant impact on how the crop responds to stress.

Environmental factors: Other environmental factors such as humidity, light intensity, and CO2 concentration can also influence how crops respond to temperature stress, so it may be useful to include information on these factors in the dataset as well.

24/03/23, 12:51 am - Anmol: The output parameter for the detection of crops under temperature stress would depend on the specific objectives of the analysis. However, some possible output parameters are:

Crop yield: One of the main impacts of temperature stress on crops is a reduction in crop yield. Therefore, an output parameter for this analysis could be the predicted or observed yield of the crop under temperature stress conditions.

Growth rate: Temperature stress can also slow down the growth of crops. Therefore, an output parameter could be the growth rate of the crop under different temperature stress conditions.

Chlorophyll content: Temperature stress can cause a reduction in the chlorophyll content of plants, which affects photosynthesis and overall plant growth. Therefore, an output parameter could be the chlorophyll content of the crop under temperature stress conditions.

Water use efficiency: Temperature stress can cause changes in plant water use efficiency, which is an important indicator of plant health and productivity. Therefore, an output parameter could be the water use efficiency of the crop under temperature stress conditions.

Biomass accumulation: Temperature stress can also affect biomass accumulation, which is an important indicator of plant growth and productivity. Therefore, an output parameter could be the biomass accumulation of the crop under different temperature stress conditions.

Stress index: The combination of different factors such as plant biomass, growth rate, chlorophyll content, and water use efficiency can be used to calculate a stress index, which provides an overall measure of the impact of temperature stress on the crop. Therefore, an output parameter could be the stress index of the crop under different temperature stress conditions.

Overall, the output parameter should be selected based on the specific research question or objective of the analysis, and should reflect the most important indicators of crop performance under temperature stress conditions.

24/03/23, 10:04 pm - Sanskar Mohan: The literature survey identified that abiotic stress, such as drought and heat stress, significantly affects crop productivity and quality, particularly in high-temperature environments. To address this issue, the researcher has developed a crop stress management system using thermal-RGB imagery and site-specific weather data through field sensing nodes, which can predict apple and cherry crop-specific abiotic stress indicators. It was found that plant responses to high temperatures are influenced by genotypic parameters, and certain genotypes are more tolerant. Approaches to improving crop productivity in high-temperature environments include manipulating leaf photosynthesis and even photosynthate partitioning. It was also found that heat stress during seed development may result in reduced germination and loss of vigor, leading to reduced emergence and seedling establishment, as shown in several crop plants. Overall, the literature survey highlights the challenges of improving crop yield and quality under changing climatic conditions and the potential of using innovative technologies for crop stress management.

09/04/23, 10:51 pm - Sanskar Mohan: def count_ones(num): 
    count = 0 
    while num > 0: 
        count+=num&1 
        num>>=1 
    return count 
 
sorted_arr = sorted(arr, key=lambda x: (count_ones(x), x))
return sorted_arr

09/04/23, 11:02 pm - Sanskar Mohan: public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(lotteryCoupons(12, 2));
    }

    public static int lotteryCoupons(int n, int maxCouponNumber) {
        int[] hash = new int[10];
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            hash[getDigitSum(i)]++;
        }
        int maxCouponCount = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < hash.length; i++) {
            if (hash[i] == maxCouponNumber) {
                maxCouponCount++;
            }
        }
        return maxCouponCount;
    }

    public static int getDigitSum(int n) {
        while (true) {
            n = getDigitSumHelper(n);
            if (n >= 0 && n <= 9) {
                return n;
            }
        }
    }

    public static int getDigitSumHelper(int n) {
        if (n == 0)
            return 0;
        return n % 10 + getDigitSumHelper(n / 10);
    }
}

        int[] hash = new int[10];
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            hash[getDigitSum(i)]++;
        }
        int maxCouponCount = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < hash.length; i++) {
            if (hash[i] == maxCouponNumber) {
                maxCouponCount++;
            }
        }

    public static int getDigitSum(int n) {
        while (true) {
            n = getDigitSumHelper(n);
            if (n >= 0 && n <= 9) {
                return n;
            }
        }
    }

    public static int getDigitSumHelper(int n) {
        if (n == 0)
            return 0;
        return n % 10 + getDigitSumHelper(n / 10);
    }

23/04/23, 10:08 am - Anmol: import java.time.Duration;
import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
import org.testng.Assert;
import org.testng.annotations.AfterClass;
import org.testng.annotations.BeforeClass;
import org.testng.annotations.Test;
import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.ExpectedConditions;
import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.WebDriverWait;
import java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;
import org.openqa.selenium.interactions.Actions;
import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.Select;
import org.openqa.selenium.Alert;

public class eval {
	WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();

    @SuppressWarnings("deprecation")
	@BeforeClass
    public void setUp() {
        // Set up the WebDriver instance
        driver = new ChromeDriver();
        driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
        driver.manage().window().maximize();
        driver.manage().deleteAllCookies();
    }

    @Test(priority = 1)
    public void loginTest() {
        // Navigate to the login page
        driver.get("https://www.saucedemo.com/");

        // Find the email and password fields and enter your credentials
        driver.findElement(By.id("user-name")).sendKeys("standard_user");
        driver.findElement(By.id("password")).sendKeys("secret_sauce");

        // Click on the login button after it becomes clickable
        WebElement loginButton = driver.findElement(By.id("login-button"));
        WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(30));
        wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(loginButton));
        loginButton.click();

        // Verify that the login was successful by checking if the user is redirected to the products page
        String currentUrl = driver.getCurrentUrl();
        Assert.assertEquals(currentUrl, "https://www.saucedemo.com/inventory.html", "Login failed!");
    }

    @Test(priority = 2)
    public void addItemToCartTest() throws InterruptedException {
        // Find the first item and add it to cart
        WebElement addToCartButton = driver.findElement(By.xpath("//*[@id=\"add-to-cart-sauce-labs-backpack\"]"));
        WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(30));
        wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(addToCartButton));
        addToCartButton.click();

        // Verify that the item was added to cart
        WebElement cartBadge = driver.findElement(By.className("shopping_cart_badge"));
        Assert.assertEquals(cartBadge.getText(), "1", "Item not added to cart!");

    }

    @Test(priority = 3)
    public void removeItemFromCartTest() {
    	// Navigate to the cart page
        driver.findElement(By.className("shopping_cart_link")).click();

        // Find the "Sauce Labs Backpack" in the cart and remove it
        WebElement removeButton = driver.findElement(By.xpath("//*[@id=\"remove-sauce-labs-backpack\"]"));
        removeButton.click();

        // Verify that the item was removed from cart
        Assert.assertTrue(driver.findElements(By.xpath("//*[@id=\"remove-sauce-labs-backpack\"]"))
                .isEmpty(), "Item not removed from cart!");
    }

    @Test(priority = 4)
    public void DragandDrop() {
    	driver.navigate().to("https://jqueryui.com/droppable/");
        driver.switchTo().frame(0);
        
        // Find the drag and drop elements
        WebElement draggable = driver.findElement(By.id("draggable"));
        WebElement droppable = driver.findElement(By.id("droppable"));
        
        // Perform the drag and drop action
        Actions actions = new Actions(driver);
        actions.dragAndDrop(draggable, droppable).build().perform();
    } 
    
    @Test(priority = 5)
    public void AlertBox() {

    driver.navigate().to("http://the-internet.herokuapp.com/javascript_alerts");
    WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver,Duration.ofSeconds(30));
    wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(By.xpath("//button[text()='Click for JS Alert']")));

    // Click the button that triggers the alert box
    driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[text()='Click for JS Alert']")).click();
    wait.until(ExpectedConditions.alertIsPresent());

    Alert alert = driver.switchTo().alert();
    String alertText = alert.getText();
    System.out.println(alertText);
    alert.accept();

    // Wait for the button that triggers a confirmation box to be clickable
    wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(By.xpath("//button[text()='Click for JS Confirm']")));
    driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[text()='Click for JS Confirm']")).click();
    
    wait.until(ExpectedConditions.alertIsPresent());
    Alert confirm = driver.switchTo().alert();
    confirm.dismiss();

    // Wait for the button that triggers a prompt box to be clickable
    wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(By.xpath("//button[text()='Click for JS Prompt']")));
    driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[text()='Click for JS Prompt']")).click();
    wait.until(ExpectedConditions.alertIsPresent());
    
    Alert prompt = driver.switchTo().alert();
    prompt.sendKeys("Hello, World!");
    prompt.accept();
    }
    
    @Test(priority = 5)
    public void DropDow() {
 // Navigate to the page with the dropdown list
    driver.get("http://demo.guru99.com/test/newtours/register.php");

    // Locate the dropdown list element
    WebElement dropdownElement = driver.findElement(By.name("country"));

    // Create a new Select object with the dropdown element
    Select dropdown = new Select(dropdownElement);

    // Select an option by its visible text
    dropdown.selectByVisibleText("ANGOLA");

    // Select an option by its value attribute
    dropdown.selectByValue("BOLIVIA");

    // Select an option by its index (starting from 0)
    dropdown.selectByIndex(3);
    }

    @AfterClass
    public void tearDown() {
        // Close the WebDriver instance
        driver.quit();
    }
}
